    "dailyBrief": {
        "brent": 86.99,
        "brentDeltaPct": 2.33,
        "bullets": [
            "An Iranian military command threatened that 'not a drop of oil' will transit the Strait of Hormuz if Iran's infrastructure is attacked, per Orinoco Tribune (unverified, single-source).",
            "Brent crude rose +2.33% over 24h to $86.99 as of 14:52 UTC, with Crisis Pressure holding in the extreme band and 379 vessels anchored or stopped at that time.",
            "PortWatch recorded 15 transits on 2026-07-19, against a pre-crisis baseline of 88/day, while Iran's closure declaration remains disputed by US/CENTCOM reports of vessels still moving."
        ],
        "date": "2026-07-23",
        "generatedAt": "2026-07-23T14:52:25.694Z",
        "source": "claude",
        "summary": "The Strait of Hormuz remains the focal point of an acute and contested maritime crisis. Iranian military command has threatened a total closure of the strait if Iran's infrastructure comes under attack, per Orinoco Tribune (unverified, single-source); the claim has not been independently confirmed. Iranian state media and the IRGC have re-declared the strait closed, but US and CENTCOM reporting disputes that characterization, noting vessels continue to transit and citing no evidence of a physical closure. Bloomberg reports three crude supertankers slipped through in recent days, consistent with the US counter-claim. PortWatch's most recent published day, 2026-07-19, recorded 15 transits against a pre-crisis baseline of 88/day, a figure four days old given PortWatch's weekly Tuesday publication cycle. Separately, port arrivals across the Hormuz-area ports over the most recent 24 hours reached 443 vessels, a distinct metric covering five ports on both the Persian Gulf and Gulf of Oman sides and not directly comparable to the PortWatch transit count. At 14:52 UTC, 379 vessels were anchored or stopped in the region. Brent had risen +2.33% over the prior 24 hours to $86.99 at that snapshot. The site's Crisis Pressure composite sits in the extreme band, driven primarily by physical transit deviation, while the Escalation Forecast composite holds in the elevated band with Polymarket escalation contracts as the top contributor. The two indices diverge: current pressure is higher-rated than the forward outlook, a gap worth watching as diplomatic signals remain contradictory.",
